This paper makes the following contributions to the field of computational drug repurposing for RDs:Methodological novelty Development of a semantically-valid negative sampling strategy combining network centrality and molecular similarity metrics to address the lack of negative associations in databases for biological associations;Empirical validation Systematic evaluation using multiple metrics (i.e. AUROC, AUPRC, Precision@K, Recall@K) across different filtering strategies and iteration-based consensus predictions, demonstrating the predictive performance of our pipeline;Practical scalability Implementation of an automated, reproducible pipeline leveraging open APIs (i.e. Monarch Initiative, DGIdb) and established ML frameworks (i.e. Node2Vec, XGBoost, GCN) that can be applied to any disease—specifically RDs.

Methodological novelty Development of a semantically-valid negative sampling strategy combining network centrality and molecular similarity metrics to address the lack of negative associations in databases for biological associations;

Empirical validation Systematic evaluation using multiple metrics (i.e. AUROC, AUPRC, Precision@K, Recall@K) across different filtering strategies and iteration-based consensus predictions, demonstrating the predictive performance of our pipeline;

Negative samples are an extremely relevant field of studies in Semantics and Network Biology [54]. Specifically, valid negative samples are all the missing links in a network that could be positive given certain conditions. For example if "Macron - president of - France" is a positive samples, "Obama - president of - France" would be a valid negative sample—while "Bread - president of - France" would be invalid, as it is semantically nonsensical. Such an approach is also defined as Contrastive Learning, and Liu et al. made a custom drug repurposing pipeline against Alzheimer’s disease and breast neoplasm by generating negative samples accordingly [55]. Hubert et al. focused on discriminating invalid negative samples from valid ones to weight them differently in a prediction [56]. Out of several approaches they took into consideration, semantic loss of function—as the degradation or failure of a system to maintain semantic validity,1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
