Results from the ML step of the pipeline with the two different models (i.e. XGBoost and GCN) vary quite a lot—both in runtime and prediction volume. Although the size of the network –thus also the size of the node embedding training file—has a role in how long and straining the training step will be, the parameter optimisation setting (i.e. ml_depth) is even more influential. The prediction itself does not take that long compared to the training. Both models have three incremental degrees of complexity for the parameter optimisation step (i.e. ‘ultralight’, ‘light’ and ‘full’). Yet, the GCN model at ml_depth=‘full’ still takes significantly less even than the XGBoost model at ml_depth=‘ultralight’.Table 4Quantitative performance metrics for single-run and consensus iteration predictions (Section “Prediction iterations as a solution for seed variability in ML methods”): AUROC, AUPRC, and F1-score values with 95% bootstrap confidence intervals demonstrate GCN’s superior discrimination ability across all configurationsModel configurationAUROC [95% CI]AUPRC [95% CI]F1P@10R@100Single-Run Performance (Full Network)GCN (raw)0.9313 [0.9222, 0.9407]0.7280 [0.6979, 0.7577]0.59221.00.1418GCN (filtered)0.9236 [0.9139, 0.9323]0.7077 [0.6752, 0.7405]0.55901.00.1400XGBoost (raw)0.3958 [0.3778, 0.4135]0.0706 [0.0649, 0.0769]0.16670.200.0069XGBoost (filtered)0.4152 [0.3950, 0.4364]0.0749 [0.0685, 0.0819]0.16670.000.0150Consensus Iterations (Subset Network)GCN (200 iterations)0.9865 [0.9764, 0.9946]0.9131 [0.8546, 0.9610]0.58991.00.9242XGBoost (10 iterations)0.4556 [0.3719, 0.5367]0.1023 [0.0678, 0.1429]0.16670.100.1667GCN achieves F1-scores comparable to Reep (F1=0.867), while Precision@10 (P@10) and Recall@100 (R@100) metrics show consensus GCN achieves perfect top-10 precision and recovers 92.42% of test edges within top-100 predictions. Filtered configurations use prob\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
