Documentation and discoverability: all development and testing steps involving the full network and smaller test networks—single or multiple iterations—are fully documented and annotated; data originates from publicly accessible databases via reproducible API calls with documented versions and parameters;

Accessibility and openness: scripts are available on Github and Gitlab in widely used file formats (e.g..py,.ipynb); data from public databases have been uploaded on Zenodo to provide reference datasets for validation even if they become unavailable from the original source;

Modularity and interoperability: pipeline functionalities are divided into distinct modules that they can be independently replaced or scaled up; input and output data structures for each module are well documented; specific modules can be readily modified to accommodate changes in integrated tools (e.g. Monarch Initiative’s V5 API);

Reproducibility and reusability: intermediate datasets are preserved at each processing step (i.e. initial, intermediate and final) in several data structures and formats (e.g. DataFrames in.csv, embeddings in.pkl) so that they can also be transformed for other research purposes that have no connection to this drug repurposing pipeline; they also have been uploaded on Zenodo.

